  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear to be legitimate (or \"clean\") by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is a federal crime under the Bank Secrecy Act of 1970, the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986, and subsequent amendments. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nSimilarly, international organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to combat money laundering globally by setting standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures.\n\nIf you have any more questions or need further clarification, feel free to ask!",
